1
00:00:00,360 --> 00:00:05,560
Today we’re gonna talk about day trading
using order blocks and how I use them in combination

2
00:00:05,560 --> 00:00:06,720
with price action.

3
00:00:06,720 --> 00:00:08,580
So, order blocks.

4
00:00:08,580 --> 00:00:14,290
These are areas with significant volume orders,
typically placed by large trading institutions.

5
00:00:14,290 --> 00:00:19,199
The key concept behind trading with order
blocks involves finding specific points in

6
00:00:19,199 --> 00:00:24,439
the market where price has experienced a substantial
upward or downward movement.

7
00:00:24,439 --> 00:00:29,850
A bullish order block is marked at a price
level where the market has displayed a strong

8
00:00:29,850 --> 00:00:33,270
advance, indicating the presence of buying
pressure.

9
00:00:33,270 --> 00:00:39,290
A bearish order block is identified when the
market has undergone a sharp decline, indicating

10
00:00:39,290 --> 00:00:40,930
selling pressure.

11
00:00:40,930 --> 00:00:46,410
The fundamental principle of order block trading
revolves around the notion that when the market

12
00:00:46,410 --> 00:00:52,120
executes a swift and substantial move, the
smart money are unable to enter their entire

13
00:00:52,120 --> 00:00:53,730
trade at once.

14
00:00:53,730 --> 00:01:00,379
So, they strategically leave pending orders
to buy or sell within the order block zone,

15
00:01:00,379 --> 00:01:05,630
anticipating that the market will retrace
back to that zone, allowing them to fill the

16
00:01:05,630 --> 00:01:08,890
remaining portion of their trading position.

17
00:01:08,890 --> 00:01:15,580
A Bullish Order Block refers to the last downward
candle or series of downward candles that

18
00:01:15,580 --> 00:01:19,130
occur before an upward impulse in price.

19
00:01:19,130 --> 00:01:23,190
It serves as a support level that pushes the
price higher.

20
00:01:23,190 --> 00:01:28,549
These order blocks signify the presence of
buy orders from institutional traders and

21
00:01:28,549 --> 00:01:34,950
banks, essentially representing an accumulation
of orders at that specific price level.

22
00:01:34,950 --> 00:01:40,979
A Bearish Order Block is the last up candle
or series of up candles before a downward

23
00:01:40,979 --> 00:01:42,740
impulse in price.

24
00:01:42,740 --> 00:01:45,009
And it will act as a resistance.

25
00:01:45,009 --> 00:01:49,750
These order blocks indicate the presence of
sell orders from institutional traders and

26
00:01:49,750 --> 00:01:54,610
banks, representing a distribution of orders
at that particular price level.

27
00:01:54,610 --> 00:01:59,619
When the price eventually breaks out of an
order block, it often retraces back into its

28
00:01:59,619 --> 00:02:00,810
range.

29
00:02:00,810 --> 00:02:06,170
This retracement offers you a chance to enter
trades within the order block range, taking

30
00:02:06,170 --> 00:02:12,020
advantage of the potential market orders that
are expected to be executed.

31
00:02:12,020 --> 00:02:17,470
A significant part of traders struggle when
it comes to effectively trading these zones,

32
00:02:17,470 --> 00:02:21,220
and one of the key factors at play is liquidity.

33
00:02:21,220 --> 00:02:26,660
Liquidity is the ability to buy or sell something
without causing a large price change.

34
00:02:26,660 --> 00:02:32,050
When a large player enters the market with
a market order, it immediately removes liquidity

35
00:02:32,050 --> 00:02:37,110
from the market because he is demanding an
immediate execution of his trade.

36
00:02:37,110 --> 00:02:42,629
His market order is then matched with someone
who has a pending order to sell.

37
00:02:42,629 --> 00:02:47,550
If the market order is bigger in size than
the opposing pending order, what will happen

38
00:02:47,550 --> 00:02:52,790
is part of the market order will be filled,
but the rest will remain unfilled.

39
00:02:52,790 --> 00:02:58,610
So the market must move higher in order to
seek out additional pending orders, to fill

40
00:02:58,610 --> 00:03:00,879
what remains of his market order.

41
00:03:00,879 --> 00:03:05,840
Essentially, this implies that pending orders
contribute liquidity to the market since they

42
00:03:05,840 --> 00:03:09,910
are the orders against which market orders
are matched.

43
00:03:09,910 --> 00:03:15,879
These pending orders act as a buffer, providing
opportunities for market orders to be executed

44
00:03:15,879 --> 00:03:20,040
without causing significant price disruptions.

45
00:03:20,040 --> 00:03:26,239
As a retail trader, your trade sizes are typically
not large enough to significantly impact market

46
00:03:26,239 --> 00:03:31,920
prices, so you rarely need to worry about
the placement and execution of our trades.

47
00:03:31,920 --> 00:03:37,240
But for large institutions however, getting
in and out of trades can be a big problem.

48
00:03:37,240 --> 00:03:42,819
Given the substantial size of the trades they
enter, professional traders face the challenge

49
00:03:42,819 --> 00:03:46,400
of minimizing their impact on the market price.

50
00:03:46,400 --> 00:03:52,640
Therefore, one of their primary goals is to
find areas in the market where there is ample

51
00:03:52,640 --> 00:03:53,640
liquidity.

52
00:03:53,640 --> 00:03:58,800
And these pockets of liquidity are often located
at levels where retail traders have placed

53
00:03:58,800 --> 00:04:00,129
their stop losses.

54
00:04:00,129 --> 00:04:06,409
The reason why stop hunts are seen frequently
in any market is down to professional traders.

55
00:04:06,409 --> 00:04:11,970
They are strategically placing large trades
with the intention of pushing the price into

56
00:04:11,970 --> 00:04:14,510
the stop loss zones.

57
00:04:14,510 --> 00:04:19,500
When it comes to order block trading, one
common rule is to consider how long the market

58
00:04:19,500 --> 00:04:21,900
has been away from a particular zone.

59
00:04:21,900 --> 00:04:27,580
It's believed that the longer the market stays
away from an order block, the higher the chance

60
00:04:27,580 --> 00:04:31,490
of a successful trade when it eventually returns.

61
00:04:31,490 --> 00:04:34,889
However, this belief is actually incorrect.

62
00:04:34,889 --> 00:04:40,430
Think about it this way: if a bank places
an order to buy or sell when the market returns

63
00:04:40,430 --> 00:04:46,330
to an order block, do you think they would
wait around for a long time for this to happen?

64
00:04:46,330 --> 00:04:50,750
No, they want to act quickly to seize the
opportunity.

65
00:04:50,750 --> 00:04:54,699
Let's compare older order blocks with more
recent zones.

66
00:04:54,699 --> 00:05:00,699
It’s clear that trading in recently created
zones tends to be more profitable than trading

67
00:05:00,699 --> 00:05:04,240
in zones that were created a long time ago.

68
00:05:04,240 --> 00:05:09,340
In simpler terms, it's better to focus on
recently created order blocks because they

69
00:05:09,340 --> 00:05:13,500
have a higher chance of resulting in successful
trades.

70
00:05:13,500 --> 00:05:19,250
Just imagine if you had traded these recent
order blocks I marked on the chart.

71
00:05:19,250 --> 00:05:22,090
Each zone would have given you a decent trade.

72
00:05:22,090 --> 00:05:27,350
But if you had traded the older zones, the
success rate is much lower.

73
00:05:27,350 --> 00:05:32,470
So here's the key takeaway: when the market
quickly returns to an order block, there's

74
00:05:32,470 --> 00:05:34,940
a higher chance of getting a successful trade.

75
00:05:34,940 --> 00:05:40,580
On the other hand, older blocks don't usually
work out well, so it's better to focus on

76
00:05:40,580 --> 00:05:44,760
zones that have been created recently.

77
00:05:44,760 --> 00:05:49,660
Another order block rule says: "The stronger
the move away from an order block, the higher

78
00:05:49,660 --> 00:05:53,800
the chance of a strong move when it eventually
returns."

79
00:05:53,800 --> 00:05:59,259
Basically, if you mark an order block on your
charts and there was a big move away from

80
00:05:59,259 --> 00:06:04,819
it, the likelihood of having a successful
trade in that zone depends on how significant

81
00:06:04,819 --> 00:06:06,000
the move was.

82
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:11,490
But here's the thing: the strength of the
move out of the zone doesn't really determine

83
00:06:11,490 --> 00:06:13,650
the success of the trade.

84
00:06:13,650 --> 00:06:19,910
Many times, you may have placed a trade at
an order block with a strong move away, only

85
00:06:19,910 --> 00:06:23,720
to see the market go straight through it when
it returns.

86
00:06:23,720 --> 00:06:28,569
This has happened to me too, and I used to
base my entries on this idea.

87
00:06:28,569 --> 00:06:34,360
The truth is, the strength of the move away
doesn't necessarily indicate how strong the

88
00:06:34,360 --> 00:06:35,520
order block is.

89
00:06:35,520 --> 00:06:41,660
Even though common teachings would consider
this a strong area, as you can see, the market

90
00:06:41,660 --> 00:06:44,389
can easily break through without stopping.

91
00:06:44,389 --> 00:06:50,050
So, it's important to understand that the
strength of the move away from an order block

92
00:06:50,050 --> 00:06:55,639
doesn't guarantee a successful trade, and
you shouldn't solely rely on it when making

93
00:06:55,639 --> 00:06:57,990
trading decisions.

94
00:06:57,990 --> 00:07:02,250
So how do you determine which order blocks
are stronger than others?

95
00:07:02,250 --> 00:07:08,020
The best order blocks must include a liquidity
run, and a break in market structure or change

96
00:07:08,020 --> 00:07:09,550
in character.

97
00:07:09,550 --> 00:07:14,680
In this example, whoever brought when the
market was down here had a lot of money at

98
00:07:14,680 --> 00:07:16,360
their disposal.

99
00:07:16,360 --> 00:07:21,560
As a trending movement increases in length,
more and more people begin trading in the

100
00:07:21,560 --> 00:07:23,190
same direction.

101
00:07:23,190 --> 00:07:27,550
Look at the last down swing before the bullish
order block is created.

102
00:07:27,550 --> 00:07:32,919
At the time of this drop a lot of traders
are beginning to go short expecting lower

103
00:07:32,919 --> 00:07:33,919
prices.

104
00:07:33,919 --> 00:07:40,139
In order for the market to be able to move
up from here, someone needs to come into the

105
00:07:40,139 --> 00:07:44,669
market and buy from all the traders who are
going short.

106
00:07:44,669 --> 00:07:47,430
This would take a huge amount of money.

107
00:07:47,430 --> 00:07:53,050
Look at this obvious liquidity run, taking
stops below this level and triggering new

108
00:07:53,050 --> 00:07:54,790
sell positions.

109
00:07:54,790 --> 00:07:56,509
This is the first condition.

110
00:07:56,509 --> 00:08:02,389
The market eventually stops falling lower
and begins advancing higher, breaking above

111
00:08:02,389 --> 00:08:06,690
the previous lower high, making a higher high.

112
00:08:06,690 --> 00:08:08,530
This is a change or character.

113
00:08:08,530 --> 00:08:10,430
The second condition.

114
00:08:10,430 --> 00:08:16,450
This bullish order block has a very high probability
of giving you a successful trade, not because

115
00:08:16,450 --> 00:08:22,479
it has a strong move away, but because we
know whoever brought down here creating the

116
00:08:22,479 --> 00:08:26,690
zone has invested a lot of money into the
market.

117
00:08:26,690 --> 00:08:31,970
So we first had a liquidity run, a change
of character, with the order block forming

118
00:08:31,970 --> 00:08:34,510
between these 2 phases.

119
00:08:34,510 --> 00:08:39,550
When price returned to this area, that was
your chance to enter, with the smart money

120
00:08:39,550 --> 00:08:42,550
positions on your side.

121
00:08:42,550 --> 00:08:43,930
Take a look here.

122
00:08:43,930 --> 00:08:49,779
First we have a significant uptrend which
is very obvious, then we have a strong, near

123
00:08:49,779 --> 00:08:51,750
vertical move down.

124
00:08:51,750 --> 00:08:57,150
This move down tells you that smart money
entered the market and absorbed all the buy

125
00:08:57,150 --> 00:09:01,280
orders from the traders going long into the
uptrend.

126
00:09:01,280 --> 00:09:06,829
Look at the obvious liquidity run, taking
stops above this level and trapping buyers

127
00:09:06,829 --> 00:09:08,410
on the wrong side.

128
00:09:08,410 --> 00:09:14,110
And as I said, the order blocks which have
the highest probability of working out successfully

129
00:09:14,110 --> 00:09:18,460
are the ones that trigger a break of structure
of a change of character.

130
00:09:18,460 --> 00:09:22,200
In this case, we have a change of character.

131
00:09:22,200 --> 00:09:23,750
Which is right here.

132
00:09:23,750 --> 00:09:29,269
The price broke below this previous higher
low, forming a new lower low.

133
00:09:29,269 --> 00:09:35,170
A bearish order block created after the market
has been going up for a long duration of time,

134
00:09:35,170 --> 00:09:40,529
and which includes a liquidity clear-out and
change of character, has a much better chance

135
00:09:40,529 --> 00:09:43,680
of working out profitably.

136
00:09:43,680 --> 00:09:49,829
In this example, we can see a bullish order
block formed after the market has been falling.

137
00:09:49,829 --> 00:09:54,490
We have lower lows and lower highs, and a
break of structure here.

138
00:09:54,490 --> 00:10:00,740
A large percentage of retail traders entered
into short trades at this point which meant

139
00:10:00,740 --> 00:10:06,380
there was a lot of profit to be made by the
banks if they came into the market and caused

140
00:10:06,380 --> 00:10:07,850
a reversal.

141
00:10:07,850 --> 00:10:13,570
When banks enter into their long trades, they
consume all the sell orders coming into the

142
00:10:13,570 --> 00:10:20,339
market and the price begins to increase, eventually
breaking the swing high found at the top of

143
00:10:20,339 --> 00:10:22,540
the last move lower.

144
00:10:22,540 --> 00:10:26,680
The previous break of structure was in fact
a liquidity run.

145
00:10:26,680 --> 00:10:28,550
And this is the change of character.

146
00:10:28,550 --> 00:10:31,880
Both of our conditions were met.

147
00:10:31,880 --> 00:10:37,000
Soon after the break of the high we see another
drop taking place.

148
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:42,370
This drop causes a lot of retail traders to
start shorting again, believing the move higher

149
00:10:42,370 --> 00:10:46,339
was simply just a pullback to the downtrend.

150
00:10:46,339 --> 00:10:51,540
When the market comes into contact with the
order block which was created by the first

151
00:10:51,540 --> 00:10:57,650
round of buying, smart money will buy again
to get more trades placed in the direction

152
00:10:57,650 --> 00:10:59,280
of the reversal.

153
00:10:59,280 --> 00:11:04,709
If the banks didn’t buy and the market fell
below the order block then they would be put

154
00:11:04,709 --> 00:11:10,180
at a loss on their positions and would have
to liquidate their buy trades.

155
00:11:10,180 --> 00:11:14,490
In this example, we spot a bearish order block.

156
00:11:14,490 --> 00:11:20,810
The market had a significant move up, followed
by a liquidity run that hits stops above this

157
00:11:20,810 --> 00:11:25,340
particular area, triggering new buy positions.

158
00:11:25,340 --> 00:11:30,810
After the liquidity run, the market starts
declining, breaking below the previous higher

159
00:11:30,810 --> 00:11:31,810
low.

160
00:11:31,810 --> 00:11:33,680
This is the change of character.

161
00:11:33,680 --> 00:11:36,750
The bearish order block forms between these
two phases.

162
00:11:36,750 --> 00:11:41,610
This area has a high probability of being
successful.

163
00:11:41,610 --> 00:11:46,790
When the price eventually revisits the order
block, it provides a chance to enter a short

164
00:11:46,790 --> 00:11:51,770
position, in line with the smart money positions.

165
00:11:51,770 --> 00:11:52,770
Another example.

166
00:11:52,770 --> 00:11:56,980
The market shows a bearish order block after
a significant uptrend.

167
00:11:56,980 --> 00:12:03,530
As the banks enter their short trades, they
absorb all the buy orders in the market, causing

168
00:12:03,530 --> 00:12:08,149
the price to decline and eventually break
the previous swing low.

169
00:12:08,149 --> 00:12:11,810
The previous break of structure was a liquidity
run.

170
00:12:11,810 --> 00:12:17,120
Lower lows and lower highs are then observed,
and this is the change of character.

171
00:12:17,120 --> 00:12:22,680
This indicates that big players entered into
short trades, providing a potential trade

172
00:12:22,680 --> 00:12:25,459
if the price returns to the order block.

173
00:12:25,459 --> 00:12:31,899
And as expected, a sharp drop takes place,
when the market revisits the order block created

174
00:12:31,899 --> 00:12:39,740
by the first round of selling, as smart money
will sell again to reinforce the reversal.

175
00:12:39,740 --> 00:12:41,590
Let's analyze another trade.

176
00:12:41,590 --> 00:12:47,590
We had a previous downtrend where the price
consistently made lower lows and lower highs.

177
00:12:47,590 --> 00:12:52,190
Now, pay attention to the first rally out
of the zone.

178
00:12:52,190 --> 00:12:58,320
During this rally, we saw bullish large range
candles that pushed the market significantly

179
00:12:58,320 --> 00:13:01,810
against the previous downward movement.

180
00:13:01,810 --> 00:13:08,220
Here's the key: Those bullish candles indicate
that there was very little selling pressure.

181
00:13:08,220 --> 00:13:13,750
It's unlikely that banks were placing sell
trades as the market rallied higher.

182
00:13:13,750 --> 00:13:19,180
The rally also managed to break the most recent
swing high.

183
00:13:19,180 --> 00:13:24,470
When you trade order blocks, the best advice
I can give you is to make sure that the zone

184
00:13:24,470 --> 00:13:28,690
you're trading breaks a recent swing high
or low.

185
00:13:28,690 --> 00:13:34,260
This break represents either a change of character
or a break in the market structure, aligning

186
00:13:34,260 --> 00:13:36,390
with the current trend.

187
00:13:36,390 --> 00:13:41,620
The reason why this change of character gives
the zone a better chance of working out, is

188
00:13:41,620 --> 00:13:47,519
partly down to the retail traders who enter
into long trades on the candle which breaks

189
00:13:47,519 --> 00:13:49,100
the swing high.

190
00:13:49,100 --> 00:13:55,150
When the market breaches a high/low traders
using technical analysis will know a possible

191
00:13:55,150 --> 00:14:01,920
trend change is taking place as the majority
of traders primarily use higher highs and

192
00:14:01,920 --> 00:14:05,910
lower lows to determine current trend direction.

193
00:14:05,910 --> 00:14:11,490
Another factor to keep in mind is the impact
of traders who find themselves stuck in losing

194
00:14:11,490 --> 00:14:15,410
trades when the market fails to make a new
swing low.

195
00:14:15,410 --> 00:14:21,790
Let me explain: When the market is close to
breaking below a swing low, breakout traders

196
00:14:21,790 --> 00:14:27,160
place orders in advance at that low, anticipating
a breakout to happen.

197
00:14:27,160 --> 00:14:34,639
Once the market moves below the low and triggers
their pending orders, they enter their trades.

198
00:14:34,639 --> 00:14:39,820
However, when the price fails to continue
moving in the direction of the breakout and

199
00:14:39,820 --> 00:14:44,699
starts moving in the opposite direction, these
breakout traders find themselves trapped in

200
00:14:44,699 --> 00:14:47,820
trades that are no longer profitable.

201
00:14:47,820 --> 00:14:54,360
At this point, often around the order block
area, these traders decide to close their

202
00:14:54,360 --> 00:14:55,400
losing trades.

203
00:14:55,400 --> 00:15:00,610
Now, here's the interesting part: When these
breakout traders start closing their losing

204
00:15:00,610 --> 00:15:05,980
trades, a significant number of buy orders
come into the market.

205
00:15:05,980 --> 00:15:11,810
This influx of buy orders actually contributes
to the upward momentum of the market.

206
00:15:11,810 --> 00:15:18,959
Now, most of the traders who trade order blocks
try to predict where a movement will end instead

207
00:15:18,959 --> 00:15:22,240
of trading in the direction of the movement
itself.

208
00:15:22,240 --> 00:15:28,089
What these traders typically tend to do is
mark all the order blocks which the market

209
00:15:28,089 --> 00:15:34,029
hasn’t encountered yet and wait for the
price to enter these zones before going either

210
00:15:34,029 --> 00:15:36,300
long or short.

211
00:15:36,300 --> 00:15:41,870
Usually these zones were created a long time
ago which means they don’t have a high chance

212
00:15:41,870 --> 00:15:44,140
of causing a reversal anyway.

213
00:15:44,140 --> 00:15:45,720
We talked about that.

214
00:15:45,720 --> 00:15:52,050
Meanwhile, as these traders wait for the market
to hit these old zones, there are plenty of

215
00:15:52,050 --> 00:15:58,150
new zones forming in the direction of the
current movement that they are ignoring.

216
00:15:58,150 --> 00:16:03,430
Instead of being so fixated on predicting
where the entire market will reverse, you

217
00:16:03,430 --> 00:16:09,440
would have more success if you focus on trading
order blocks that form in the direction of

218
00:16:09,440 --> 00:16:11,330
the most recent high or low.

219
00:16:11,330 --> 00:16:18,769
A new high or low in the trend, meaning a
break of structure, or a BOS, is a signal

220
00:16:18,769 --> 00:16:25,600
that the current momentum is to the upside
or downside, by trading against this momentum

221
00:16:25,600 --> 00:16:30,590
you are unnecessarily putting yourself at
risk of losing money because you’re trying

222
00:16:30,590 --> 00:16:33,009
to trade against the trend.

223
00:16:33,009 --> 00:16:37,269
Let's take a look at an example to illustrate
this point.

224
00:16:37,269 --> 00:16:42,700
Imagine a trader who had already marked a
bearish order block on their charts before

225
00:16:42,700 --> 00:16:44,769
the price made a new high.

226
00:16:44,769 --> 00:16:50,720
However, when a bullish move occurred and
a new high was reached, instead of recognizing

227
00:16:50,720 --> 00:16:57,250
it as a signal that the price wants to continue
moving higher, the trader decides to place

228
00:16:57,250 --> 00:17:03,019
a short trade because he believes the order
block will cause a market reversal.

229
00:17:03,019 --> 00:17:09,610
And, after reaching the marked area, the price
only experiences a small drop before breaking

230
00:17:09,610 --> 00:17:16,949
higher again, forming another new high and
creating a bullish order block in the process.

231
00:17:16,949 --> 00:17:22,970
When the market returns to this area, it triggers
another upward movement.

232
00:17:22,970 --> 00:17:28,549
By always trading in the direction of the
most recent high or low, you give yourself

233
00:17:28,549 --> 00:17:31,780
the best opportunity to have winning trades.

234
00:17:31,780 --> 00:17:37,460
It's important to recognize the current momentum
and follow the direction indicated by the

235
00:17:37,460 --> 00:17:44,309
most recent high or low, rather than trying
to predict reversals based solely on order

236
00:17:44,309 --> 00:17:45,309
blocks.

237
00:17:45,309 --> 00:17:50,549
Here another example of an order block after
a break of structure.

238
00:17:50,549 --> 00:17:55,990
Remember what I previously said: the quicker
the price returns to the order block the more

239
00:17:55,990 --> 00:17:59,440
likely you are to end up with a profitable
trade.

240
00:17:59,440 --> 00:18:04,909
When the price moves up or down, forming a
trading zone, it's possible that banks and

241
00:18:04,909 --> 00:18:11,320
large traders may have remaining trades that
they were not able to execute during that

242
00:18:11,320 --> 00:18:12,500
initial movement.

243
00:18:12,500 --> 00:18:18,610
In such cases, these market participants may
choose to take some profits off their trades

244
00:18:18,610 --> 00:18:24,610
and manipulate the market to return to the
region where their remaining trades were intended

245
00:18:24,610 --> 00:18:25,610
to be placed.

246
00:18:25,610 --> 00:18:30,110
This allows them to enter the rest of their
positions into the market.

247
00:18:30,110 --> 00:18:38,320
In this example, when the price shoots up
creating the order block and forming the BOS,

248
00:18:38,320 --> 00:18:42,143
the banks still have a few more buy trades
left which they need to be placed.

249
00:18:42,143 --> 00:18:47,890
To bring the price back into the trading zone,
banks may take some profits from their existing

250
00:18:47,890 --> 00:18:49,500
buy trades.

251
00:18:49,500 --> 00:18:55,890
By doing so, the buy orders that were supporting
the price are consumed, resulting in a downward

252
00:18:55,890 --> 00:18:56,890
movement.

253
00:18:56,890 --> 00:19:02,549
As the price falls into the region where the
banks initially placed their buy trades, they

254
00:19:02,549 --> 00:19:07,650
leverage the new sell orders that have entered
the market due to the drop.

255
00:19:07,650 --> 00:19:13,740
These sell orders are generated by traders
on lower timeframes who are selling in response

256
00:19:13,740 --> 00:19:15,280
to the price decline.

257
00:19:15,280 --> 00:19:22,090
The banks utilize these sell orders to facilitate
the execution of the remaining buy trades

258
00:19:22,090 --> 00:19:25,809
they intended to enter into the market.

259
00:19:25,809 --> 00:19:30,600
Let's consider another instance of an order
block following a break of structure.

260
00:19:30,600 --> 00:19:37,220
In this particular example, we see the price
moving down, creating the order block and

261
00:19:37,220 --> 00:19:40,580
forming the break of Structure (BOS).

262
00:19:40,580 --> 00:19:46,410
If the banks still have some sell trades remaining
that were not executed when the price initially

263
00:19:46,410 --> 00:19:52,030
formed the order block, they will book some
profits from their existing sell trades and

264
00:19:52,030 --> 00:19:57,830
manipulate the market to move back into the
area where their trades were intended.

265
00:19:57,830 --> 00:20:04,080
So to entice the price to rise into the order
block zone, the banks may take partial profits

266
00:20:04,080 --> 00:20:05,900
from their sell trades.

267
00:20:05,900 --> 00:20:11,630
Once the price reaches the region where the
banks initially placed their first sell trades,

268
00:20:11,630 --> 00:20:17,780
they utilize the newly emerged buy orders
from traders on lower timeframes, who entered

269
00:20:17,780 --> 00:20:21,010
buy positions due to the upward movement.

270
00:20:21,010 --> 00:20:27,710
These buy orders assist the banks in executing
the remaining of their sell trades.

271
00:20:27,710 --> 00:20:33,520
You can see how the banks strategically navigate
the market to maximize their trade entries

272
00:20:33,520 --> 00:20:37,950
while maintaining control over price movements.

273
00:20:37,950 --> 00:20:43,330
When I started trading order blocks, I used
to enter trades by placing pending orders

274
00:20:43,330 --> 00:20:47,790
at the zones, which is a common approach in
many trading methods.

275
00:20:47,790 --> 00:20:55,059
However, I discovered that using pending orders
at the order blocks often resulted in losses.

276
00:20:55,059 --> 00:21:00,650
The market would often disregard the zone
and continue moving strongly in the opposite

277
00:21:00,650 --> 00:21:04,809
direction, causing my trades to fail almost
immediately.

278
00:21:04,809 --> 00:21:10,529
Many times when I first began trading these
zones, I found many order blocks which met

279
00:21:10,529 --> 00:21:16,380
all the criteria, but when it came to trading
these zones with pending orders most of the

280
00:21:16,380 --> 00:21:23,309
time the market would just blow past the zone
and I would almost instantly lose my trades.

281
00:21:23,309 --> 00:21:30,720
One way is to navigate on lower time frames,
and try to find another OB or a break of structure

282
00:21:30,720 --> 00:21:32,780
or a change of character.

283
00:21:32,780 --> 00:21:35,310
And this is a valid way to enter.

284
00:21:35,310 --> 00:21:38,580
Using candlestick patterns to enter trades
is another method.

285
00:21:38,580 --> 00:21:44,559
I like to use pin bars and engulfing candles
as my trigger for entering trades at order

286
00:21:44,559 --> 00:21:46,320
blocks.

287
00:21:46,320 --> 00:21:51,770
The strongest price action setup you can use
in conjunction with order blocks is the engulfing

288
00:21:51,770 --> 00:21:53,340
candle.

289
00:21:53,340 --> 00:21:58,150
Engulfing candles, when found around order
blocks show you that bank traders have an

290
00:21:58,150 --> 00:22:02,250
interest in making the market move away from
a zone.

291
00:22:02,250 --> 00:22:07,540
The candle itself is the result of bank traders
entering into the market.

292
00:22:07,540 --> 00:22:13,910
The way we would have traded this is by first
locating the order block on our charts, then,

293
00:22:13,910 --> 00:22:19,390
when the market returns to the zone we will
switch to a lower time frame to see if an

294
00:22:19,390 --> 00:22:25,130
engulfing candle appears, which we can use
as an entry trigger into our trades.

295
00:22:25,130 --> 00:22:30,140
When switching to lower time frames to look
for trades I suggest you go no lower than

296
00:22:30,140 --> 00:22:31,909
the 5 minute chart.

297
00:22:31,909 --> 00:22:37,090
It's important to avoid going too low in time
frames, such as the 1-minute chart, as it

298
00:22:37,090 --> 00:22:40,840
can generate many false signals.

299
00:22:40,840 --> 00:22:45,150
Here we are looking at an order block on the
5 minute chart, we can see an engulfing candle

300
00:22:45,150 --> 00:22:49,190
appears shortly after price entered the zone.

301
00:22:49,190 --> 00:22:54,039
This is your trigger for entering the trade,
when you see this candle form.

302
00:22:54,039 --> 00:22:58,840
While it's possible to enter trades using
the same time frame on which the order block

303
00:22:58,840 --> 00:23:03,460
is identified, it is often beneficial to switch
to a lower time frame.

304
00:23:03,460 --> 00:23:09,360
By doing so, you can reduce your risk and
potentially increase your reward.

305
00:23:09,360 --> 00:23:14,000
If you chose to enter the market based on
the engulfing candle observed on this time

306
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:18,960
frame, for example, the distance between your
entry point and the stop-loss level would

307
00:23:18,960 --> 00:23:20,990
be 20 pips.

308
00:23:20,990 --> 00:23:26,049
However, if you switched to a lower chart,
and entered the trade based on the engulfing

309
00:23:26,049 --> 00:23:31,230
candle seen there, your risk would be reduced
to only 10 pips.

310
00:23:31,230 --> 00:23:36,350
By doing so, you have effectively decreased
the risk on the trade by 50%.

311
00:23:36,350 --> 00:23:43,340
Over a series of 10 to 20 trades, this reduction
in risk can accumulate to a significant amount

312
00:23:43,340 --> 00:23:45,770
of money saved or earned.

313
00:23:45,770 --> 00:23:51,700
Furthermore, by entering the trade on lower
chart using the engulfing candle, you not

314
00:23:51,700 --> 00:23:56,230
only decreased your risk but also you increased
the potential gain.

315
00:23:56,230 --> 00:24:01,690
This is because your entry occurred right
at the beginning of the downward movement.

316
00:24:01,690 --> 00:24:06,820
If you had traded based on the engulfing candle
seen on the higher time frame, you would have

317
00:24:06,820 --> 00:24:11,220
entered the trade after the market had already
moved down slightly.

318
00:24:11,220 --> 00:24:17,409
As a result, the potential profit you could
make from the trade would have decreased.

319
00:24:17,409 --> 00:24:22,080
The two candles which make up an engulfing
pattern are directly linked to whether the

320
00:24:22,080 --> 00:24:24,780
zone is likely to work out or not.

321
00:24:24,780 --> 00:24:27,539
I want you to look at this engulfing pattern.

322
00:24:27,539 --> 00:24:31,870
There’s two candles which make up this engulfing
structure.

323
00:24:31,870 --> 00:24:39,120
The first is a small bullish candle and the
second is this bearish engulfing candle.

324
00:24:39,120 --> 00:24:44,799
Whenever you see a small candlestick engulfed
by a large candlestick in an order block,

325
00:24:44,799 --> 00:24:50,700
it’s a good indication that the market is
going to move out of the order block.

326
00:24:50,700 --> 00:24:56,270
The first bullish candle makes retail traders
think the market is going up, so they begin

327
00:24:56,270 --> 00:24:57,390
to buy.

328
00:24:57,390 --> 00:25:02,711
And when the engulfing candle shows up and
pushes the market down really quickly, it

329
00:25:02,711 --> 00:25:08,909
has the effect of putting the buyers under
intense pressure to close their positions.

330
00:25:08,909 --> 00:25:14,399
This is the important bit, the aspect of how
time affects the actions of the traders.

331
00:25:14,399 --> 00:25:20,289
If the bearish engulfing candle was small
and only just managed to engulf the small

332
00:25:20,289 --> 00:25:26,370
bullish candle, the buyers would feel less
compelled to close their trades, the loss

333
00:25:26,370 --> 00:25:32,059
they are in is small, therefore they would
be more willing to continue holding their

334
00:25:32,059 --> 00:25:33,059
trades.

335
00:25:33,059 --> 00:25:38,680
When the engulfing candle is big, the traders
are faced with a loss much greater.

336
00:25:38,680 --> 00:25:43,659
This is the reason these types of engulfing
structures tend to work so well.

337
00:25:43,659 --> 00:25:50,270
As the loss for traders who have bought increases,
they become more inclined to close their positions.

338
00:25:50,270 --> 00:25:55,700
This action of closing their losing trades
can create a swift movement away from the

339
00:25:55,700 --> 00:25:58,000
order block.

340
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:02,789
The other price action signal you’re able
to use when looking for entries into order

341
00:26:02,789 --> 00:26:04,760
blocks is the pin bar.

342
00:26:04,760 --> 00:26:10,029
Pin bars, as you should already know, show
a rejection is taking place in the market,

343
00:26:10,029 --> 00:26:15,120
usually from a support and resistance level
or recent swing highs and lows.

344
00:26:15,120 --> 00:26:16,930
Here’s an order block.

345
00:26:16,930 --> 00:26:22,320
When price returns to the zone you will then
need to switch to a lower time frame to look

346
00:26:22,320 --> 00:26:27,289
for a pin bar that you can use as an entry
trigger into your trade.

347
00:26:27,289 --> 00:26:32,770
As you can see when the market enters the
zone it produces a bearish pin bar.

348
00:26:32,770 --> 00:26:38,490
The way you would have traded this would be
to first wait for the pin bar to close, then

349
00:26:38,490 --> 00:26:41,789
you place a trade sell trade using a market
order.

350
00:26:41,789 --> 00:26:46,200
with the stop-loss placed above the high of
the pin.

351
00:26:46,200 --> 00:26:51,740
In this example, we have a pin bar formation
on the 4-hour chart.

352
00:26:51,740 --> 00:26:56,539
While you could potentially trade this setup
directly from the 4-hour chart, it is more

353
00:26:56,539 --> 00:27:02,789
advantageous to decrease risk and increase
potential profit by scanning lower time frames

354
00:27:02,789 --> 00:27:05,220
for additional pin bars.

355
00:27:05,220 --> 00:27:11,080
Looking at the 30-minute chart, we can see
another pin bar within the same order block

356
00:27:11,080 --> 00:27:12,080
zone.

357
00:27:12,080 --> 00:27:18,210
It's interesting how this pin bar is actually
nested within the larger pin bar seen on the

358
00:27:18,210 --> 00:27:19,460
4-hour chart.

359
00:27:19,460 --> 00:27:23,340
To trade this setup, we would follow the same
approach as before.

360
00:27:23,340 --> 00:27:29,830
We would enter a buy trade once the pin bar
has closed, placing our stop-loss order below

361
00:27:29,830 --> 00:30:04,050
the low of the pin bar.

